[[File:Färbewerkstatt1.jpg|right|thumb|Dyeing in the Middle Ages.]]
<!-- This article uses a [[Wikipedia:Manual of Style (glossaries)#Structured glossaries|structured glossary]] format. -->
<!-- The standard used in this glossary is to link common names used in dyeing (piped to Latin name as needed). Link Latin names only if there are separate articles under the common and Latin names. -->

:''This glossary contains terms specific to [[dyeing]]. For terms used in the creation or manufacturing of textiles, including spinning, knitting, weaving, and individual fabrics and finishing processes, see [[Glossary of textile manufacturing]]. For terms used in [[sewing]] and [[tailor]]ing, see [[Glossary of sewing terms]].''
'''[[Dyeing]]''' is the [[craft]] of imparting [[colors]] to [[textile]]s in loose [[fibre|fiber]], [[yarn]], cloth or garment form by treatment with a [[dye]]. [[Archeology|Archaeologists]] have found evidence of [[textile]] dyeing with [[natural dye]]s dating back to the [[Neolithic]] period. In China, dyeing with plants, barks and insects has been traced back more than 5,000 years.<ref name="Goodwin11">Goodwin (1982), p. 11.</ref> Natural insect dyes such as [[Tyrian purple]] and [[kermes (dye)|kermes]] and plant-based dyes such as [[isatis tinctoria|woad]], [[Indigo dye|indigo]] and [[rubia|madder]] were important elements of the economies of Asia and Europe until the discovery of man-made [[dye|synthetic dyes]] in the mid-19th century. Synthetic dyes quickly superseded natural dyes for the large-scale commercial textile production enabled by the [[industrial revolution]], but natural dyes remained in use by traditional cultures around the world.

{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==A==
{{glossary}}
{{term|aal}}
{{defn|1=[[Morinda tinctoria|Aal]] or Indian mulberry (''Morinda tinctoria'') is the source of the [[morindone]] dye sold under the trade name "Suranji". It is extensively cultivated in [[India]] for the dyeing of [[cotton]], [[silk]] and [[wool]] in shades of red, chocolate or purple, dependent on the [[mordant]] used.}}
{{term|adjective}}
{{defn|1=Adjective dyes are those dyes that require use of a [[mordant]] to bind the color to the [[fibre|fiber]].<ref name="Cannon13">Cannon & Cannon (2002), p. 13</ref>}}
{{term|alkanet}}
{{defn|1=[[Alkanna tinctoria|Alkanet]] or dyer's bugloss (''Alkanna tinctoria'') is a traditional plant source of red dye.<ref name="Barber232">Barber (1991), p. 232.</ref> }}
{{term|alum}}
{{defn|1=[[Alum]] (aluminum sulfate) is a naturally occurring basic [[mordant]] widely used in the ancient world.<ref name="Barber235"/>}}
{{term|term=añil |content=añil {{anchor|anil}} }}
{{defn|1=[[Indigofera suffruticosa|Añil]] (''Indigofera suffruticosa'') is an [[indigo dye]]-bearing plant of [[Central America|Central]] and [[South America]].<ref name="Indigo">See [[Indigo dye]].</ref><ref name="Goodwin70"/>}}
{{term|aniline}}
{{defn|1=[[Aniline]] dyes or basic dyes are a class of synthetic dyes derived from coal tar, first discovered in the 19th century. These dyes produce brilliant colors that work well with animal fibers, especially [[silk]]. Because of poor colorfastness, aniline dyes are seldom used with textiles today.<ref name="Thompson10">Thompson & Thompson (1987), p. 10</ref>}}
{{term|archil}}
{{defn|1=[[Orcein|Archil]] is a dye produced from the [[lichen]] ''Roccella tinctoria'' which also produces [[cudbear]] and [[litmus]].<ref name="Goodwin87">Goodwin (1982), pp. 87–92.</ref>}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==B==
{{glossary}}
{{term|bloodroot}}
{{defn|1=[[Bloodroot]] (''Sanguinaria canadensis'') or puccoon is a [[Perennial plant|perennial]], [[herbaceous]] [[flowering plant]] native to eastern [[North America]] that is the source for a red dye used by [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]].<ref>Chancey, p. 37</ref> }}
{{term|brazilwood}}
{{defn|1=Brazilwood is a red-brown dye from either of two related trees. The original brazilwood,
[[Caesalpinia sappan|sappan wood]] (''Caesalpinia sappan''), is native to India and was exported to China by 900 BCE and to Europe via the Muslim world by the [[Early Middle Ages]]. [[Portugal|Portuguese]] explorers discovered a similar tree growing in the [[New World]] and named the surrounding country [[Brazil]]. This tree is the [[Caesalpinia echinata|Brazilwood]] (''Caesalpinia echinata'') used by contemporary craft dyers.<ref name="Cannon36">Cannon & Cannon (2002), p. 36</ref>}}
{{term|black walnut}}
{{defn|1=[[Black walnut]] (''[[Juglans nigra]]'') is a [[North America]]n tree used to produce a deep brown dye approaching black.}}{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==C==
{{glossary}}
{{term|carmine}}
{{defn|1=[[Carmine]] is a [[crimson]]-colored dye derived from [[cochineal]] (''Dactylopius coccus''), a [[scale insect]] of [[Central America|Central]] and [[North America]].<ref name="tym">{{cite web |author=Threads In Tyme, LTD |title=Time line of fabrics |url=http://threadsintyme.tripod.com/id63.htm | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051028155009/http://threadsintyme.tripod.com/id63.htm | archivedate=2005-10-28 | accessdate=5 January 2011}}</ref>}}
{{term|cochineal}}
{{defn|1=[[Cochineal]] (''Dactylopius coccus'') is a [[scale insect]] of [[Central America|Central]] and [[North America]] from which the [[crimson]]-coloured dye [[carmine]] is derived.<ref name="tym" />}}
{{term|colorfast}}
{{defn|1=[[Colour fastness|Colorfast]] dyes are dyes resistant to shifts in hue, fading, or bleeding (transfer of dye) when wet.<ref>Kadolph (2007), p. 464</ref> }}
{{term|copperas}}
{{defn|1=Copperas is the dyer's name for [[ferrous sulfate]], an iron [[mordant]] used to ''sadden'' or reduce the saturation of colors.<ref name="Barber235">Barber (1991), pp. 235-236, 239.</ref><ref name="Goodwin32">Goodwin (1982), pp. 32–34.</ref>
}}
{{term|crimson}}
{{defn|1=[[Crimson]] is a deep red dye or color derived from the word ''kermes''.<ref name="Barber 1991, p. 231">Barber (1991), p. 231</ref><ref name="Munro214">Munro, John H. "Medieval Woollens: Textiles, Technology, and Organisation". In Jenkins (2003), pp. 214–215.</ref><ref name="Goodwin56">Goodwin (1982), p. 56</ref>}}
{{term|crottle}}
{{defn|1=Crottle is a [[Traditional dyes of the Scottish Highlands|traditional Scottish dye]] derived from [[lichen]]s of the genus ''[[Parmelia (lichen)|Parmelia]]'', ''[[Parmelia saxatilis]]'' and ''[[Parmelia omphalodes]]'', which give deep red- or purple-brown and rusty orange respectively.<ref>Fraser, Jean: ''Traditional Scottish Dyes'', Canongate, 1983</ref> These lichens are the origin of the distinctive scent of naturally dyed [[Harris Tweed]].<ref name="Goodwin87" />}}
{{term|cudbear}}
{{defn|1=[[Cudbear]] is a purple dye from the [[lichen]] ''Roccella tinctoria'' which also produces [[Orcein|archil]] and [[litmus]]. Cudbear is one of the few [[natural dye]]s to be credited to a named individual, Dr Cuthbert Gordon of [[Scotland]], who [[patent]]ed the process of its production in 1758.<ref name="Goodwin87"/>
}}
{{term|cutch}}
{{defn|1=[[Catechu|Cutch]] is an ancient brown dye from the wood of acacia trees, particularly ''[[acacia catechu]]'', used in India for dyeing [[cotton]]. Cutch gives gray-browns with an iron mordant and olive-browns with copper.<ref>Goodwin (1982), p. 60.</ref>}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==D==
{{glossary}}
{{term|direct dye}}
{{defn|1=''Same as'' [[#substantive|substantive]].}}
{{term|dye}}
{{defn|1=[[Dye]]s are [[color]]-bearing [[organic compounds]] that can be dissolved in water or another liquid so that they will penetrate fibers.<ref>Kadolph (2007), p. 384</ref>}}
{{term|dyebath}}
{{defn|1=A dyebath is a solution of dye and water or other liquid in which textiles are dyed.<ref>Thompson & Thompson (1987), p. 123</ref>}}
{{term|dyed in the wool}}
{{defn|1=''Dyed in the wool'' or ''dyed in the fleece'' refers to [[fibre|fibers]] that are dyed prior to [[spinning (textiles)|spinning]]. Compare to ''dyed in the hank'' or ''yarn-dyed''; ''piece-dyed'' (dyed after [[weaving]]); and ''garment-dyed'', dyed after [[sewing]] or [[knitting]].}}
{{term|dyer's broom}}
{{defn|1=[[Genista tinctoria|Dyer's broom]] (''Genista tinctoria''), also known as dyer's greenweed or dyer's greenwood, is a garden plant used to produce yellow dyes.<ref name="florilegium">[http://www.florilegium.org/files/TEXTILES/green-art.html Stefan's Florilegium].</ref>}}
{{term|dyer's bugloss}}
{{defn|1=[[Alkanna tinctoria|Dyer's bugloss]] (''Alkanna tinctoria'') is the source of the red dye [[#alkanet|alkanet]].<ref name="Barber232" />}}
{{term|dyer's knotweed}}
{{defn|1=[[Polygonum tinctorum|Dyer's knotweed]] (''Polygonum tinctorum'') is an [[indigo dye|indigo]]-bearing dye plant native to Japan and the coasts of China.<ref name="Goodwin70">Goodwin (1982), pp. 11, 70-76</ref>}}
{{term|dyer's mulberry tree}}
{{defn|1=[[Maclura tinctoria|Dyer's mulberry tree]] (''Maclura tinctoria'') is a New World tree from which the dye old fustic is derived.<ref name="Goodwin60" />}}
{{term|dyer's rocket}}
{{defn|1=''Same as'' [[#weld|weld]].}}
{{term|dyestuff}}
{{defn|1=Dyestuff is any raw material that releases a dye.}}
{{term|dyeworks}}
{{defn|1=A dyeworks, dye-works, or dye works is a workshop for dyeing fiber, yarn, or cloth.}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==F==
{{glossary}}
{{term|fast}}
{{defn|1=''Same as'' [[#colorfast|colorfast]]}}
{{term|fugitive}}
{{defn|1=Fugitive colors are prone to fading when exposed to sunlight (''fugitive to light'') or washing, as opposed to colorfast.}}
{{term|fustic}}
{{defn|1=[[Maclura tinctoria|Fustic]] or ''old fustic'' is a brilliant yellow dye derived from the inner bark of the dyer's mulberry tree ''Maclura tinctoria'' of the [[West Indies]] and [[Mexico]].<ref name="Goodwin60">Goodwin (1982), p. 60</ref>}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==G==
{{glossary}}
{{term|gall nut}}
{{defn|1=[[oak apple|Gall nuts]], nutgalls or oak apples are a [[tannin]]-rich growth on oak trees produced by an infection of the insect ''[[Cynips gallae tinctoriae]]'', used as a dye and a [[mordant]]. Commercial gall nuts are harvested from the [[Quercus lusitanica|Gall Oak]] (''Quercus lusitanica''), also called Lusitanian Oak or Dyer's Oak, native to [[Morocco]], [[Portugal]], and [[Spain]].}}
{{term|garment-dyed}}
{{defn|1=Dyed after [[sewing]] or [[knitting]].}}
{{term|grain}}
{{defn|1=Grain was the [[Middle Ages|Medieval]] word for the red insect dye [[kermes (dye)|kermes]]. ''Dyed in the grain'' refers to dyed with kermes, or kermes in combination with another dye, producing colors such as ''crimson in grain'', ''violet in grain''.<ref name="Munro214" />}}
{{glossary end}}

==I==
{{glossary}}
{{term|Indian madder}}
{{defn|1=[[rubia|Indian madder]] or munjeet (''Rubia cordifolia'') is native to the [[Himalaya Mountains|Himalayas]] and other mountains of Asia and Japan. Munjeet was an important dye for the Asian cotton industry and is still used by craft dyers in Nepal.<ref>Cannon & Cannon (2002), p. 80.</ref>}}
{{term|indigo}}
{{defn|1=[[Indigo]] is a deep blue derived from any of the [[indigo dye]]-bearing plants, primarily those in the genus ''[[Indigofera]]'', especially true indigo (''[[Indigofera tinctoria]]'', also known as ''Indigofera sumatrana'').<ref name="Indigo" /><ref name="Goodwin70"/>}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==K==
{{glossary}}
{{term|Kendal green}}
{{defn|1=Kendal green is a coarse gray-green [[woolen]] cloth created by [[mordant]]ing wool in [[alum]], dyeing it yellow with [[broom|dyer's broom]], and then overdyeing the cloth blue with [[isatis tinctoria|woad]] (or later, [[indigo dye|indigo]]). It is named for [[Kendal]], [[Cumbria]] (formerly part of [[Westmorland]]) where the cloth was made from the [[Middle Ages]].<ref>Kerridge (1988), p. 20</ref> }}

{{term|kermes}}
{{defn|1=[[Kermes (dye)|Kermes]] is a [[natural dye]] derived from the dried unlaid eggs of the females of a [[scale insect]] in the genus ''[[Kermes (genus)|Kermes]]'', primarily ''[[Kermes vermilio]]'', distantly related to the [[cochineal]] insect, and found on species of [[oak]] (especially [[Kermes oak]]) near the [[Mediterranean]].<ref name="Barber 1991, p. 231"/><ref name="Munro214" /><ref name="Goodwin56" /> }}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==L==
{{glossary}}
{{term|Lincoln green}}
{{defn|1=[[Lincoln green]] is a warm olive green dye produced in [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]] in the [[Middle Ages]], made by dyeing wool blue with [[Isatis tinctoria|woad]], then overdyeing it yellow with [[Reseda (plant)|weld]]<ref>[http://www.alchemy-works.com/reseda_luteola.html ''Reseda luteola'']</ref> or [[Genista tinctoria|dyers' broom]].<ref name="florilegium" />}}
{{term|logwood}}
{{defn|1=[[Haematoxylum campechianum|Logwood]] (''Haematoxylum campechianum'') is a dyewood native to [[Mexico]] and [[Central America]] which produces a fast black in combination with a [[ferrous sulfate]] (copperas) mordant.<ref name="Munro87">Munro (2007), pp. 87–93.</ref> Despite changing fashions in color, logwood was the most widely used dye by the 19th century, providing the sober blacks of formal and [[mourning]] clothes.<ref name="Schoeser118">Schoeser (2007), p. 118</ref>
}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==M==
{{glossary}}
{{term|madder}}
{{defn|1=[[rubia|Madder]] (''rubia tinctoria'') and related plants of the ''Rubia'' family are a source of good red dyes containing [[alizarin]] and [[1,2,4-Trihydroxyanthraquinone|purpurin]]. Madder was a dye of commercial importance in Europe, being cultivated in the Netherlands and France until the market collapsed following the development of synthetic [[alizarin]] dye in 1869.<ref name="Goodwin64">Goodwin (1982), pp. 64-65</ref>}}
{{term|mauveine}}
{{defn|1=[[Mauveine]] or [[aniline]] [[purple]] was the first synthetic [[organic chemistry|organic chemical]] [[dye]].<ref>{{Cite journal
