==O==
{{glossary}}
{{term|oak gall}}
{{defn|1=''Same as'' [[#gall nut|gall nut]].}}
{{term|ochre}}
{{defn|1=[[Ochre]] is an [[iron oxide]] [[pigment]] from [[clay]] that can be used to dye textiles a ruddy or reddish-brown color. Evidence of textile dyeing with ochre has been dated to the [[Neolithic]].<ref name="Barber223">Barber (1991), pp. 223-225.</ref> }}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==P==
{{glossary}}
{{term|Phoenician red}}
{{defn|1=Phoenician red is a red dye related to [[Tyrian purple]] or royal purple, extracted from several genera of [[sea snail]]s, primarily ''[[Murex brandaris]]'' the spiny dye-murex (currently known as ''Bolinus brandaris'').<ref name="Barber228">Barber (1991), pp. 228-229</ref>}}
{{term|pigment}}
{{defn|1=[[Pigment]]s are insoluble color particles that may be attached to the surface of cloth using a binding agent. Solutions of binders and pigments are called ''pigment dyes''.<ref name="Kadolph383">Kadolph (2007), p. 383.</ref>}}
{{term|Polish cochineal}}
{{defn|1=[[Polish cochineal]] or Polish grains is a [[crimson]] dye colloquially known as "Saint John's blood", produced in [[Eastern Europe]] during the [[Middle Ages]] from the [[scale insect]] ''Porphyrophora polonica''.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}} }}
{{term|potash}}
{{defn|1=[[Potash]] ([[potassium carbonate]]) is a common [[mordant]] made by [[Leaching (chemical science)|leaching]] wood ashes and evaporating the solution.<ref name="Goodwin32" />}}

{{term|prepared for dyeing}}
{{defn|1=A fabric or garment which is ''prepared for dyeing'', abbreviated PFD, is specially made to be [[dye]]d. PFD fabrics have been [[desizing|desized]], scoured, and fully [[bleach]]ed, but have been processed without [[optical brightener]]s or softeners which can interfere with dye uptake.<ref>[http://list.emich.edu/~dyers/pdfs/dyeglossary.PDF Dyes and Dyeing Glossary: A Glossary of Terms for Materials and Processes in Textile Dyeing for Artists]</ref>
}}
{{term|puccoon}}
{{defn|1=''Same as'' [[#bloodroot|bloodroot]].}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==Q==
{{glossary}}
{{term|quercitron}}
{{defn|1=[[Quercitron]] is a yellow natural dye obtained from the bark of the [[Quercus velutina|Eastern Black Oak]] (''Quercus velutina''), a forest tree indigenous in North America.<ref>Cannon & Cannon (2002), p. 28</ref>}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==R==
{{glossary}}
{{term|reactive dye}}
{{defn|1=[[Reactive dye]]s are a class of synthetic dyes that first appeared commercially in 1956, after their invention in 1954 by Rattee and Stephens at the [[Imperial Chemical Industries]] Dyestuffs Division site in the [[United Kingdom]]. Reactive dyes are used primarily to dye natural fibers and [[cellulose]] fibers such as [[rayon]].<ref name="Kadolph482">Kadolph (2007), p. 482</ref>}}
{{term|resist dyeing}}
{{defn|1=[[Resist dyeing]] and the related resist printing are terms for a number of traditional methods of dyeing textiles with patterns. Methods are used to "resist" or prevent the dye from reaching all the cloth, thereby creating a pattern and ground. The most common forms use wax, some type of paste, or a mechanical resist that manipulates the cloth such as tying or stitching. Resist techniques include [[Screen printing]], [[tie-dye]], [[ikat]], and [[batik]].<ref name="Kadolph482" />}}
{{term|royal purple}}
{{defn|1=[[Tyrian purple]] or royal purple is a purple-red dye which is extracted from several genera of [[sea snail]]s, primarily ''[[Murex brandaris]]'' the spiny dye-murex (currently known as ''Bolinus brandaris''). Murex dye was greatly prized in antiquity because it did not fade, rather it became brighter and more intense with weathering and sunlight.<ref name="Barber228"/>}}
{{term|rubia}}
{{defn|1=''[[Rubia]]'' is a family of plants that are sources of the red dye [[#madder|madder]].<ref name="Goodwin64" />}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==S==
{{glossary}}
{{term|safflower}}
{{defn|1=[[Safflower]] (''Carthamus tinctorius'') is a flowering plant natuve to Asia that produces a [[#substantive|substantive]] yellow dye for natural fibers. Dried safflower blossoms can be used to produce yellow, mustard, khaki, olive green and red colors. Cotton tape dyed red with safflower was formerly used to tie up government papers in [[United Kingdom|Britain]], giving rise to the term [[red tape]].<ref>Cannon & Cannon (2002), p. 92</ref>}}
{{term|saffron}}
{{defn|1=[[Saffron]] is a spice derived from the flower of the saffron [[crocus]] (''Crocus sativus'') that produces a golden-yellow [[carotenoid]] dye called [[crocin]].<ref>Cannon & Cannon (2002), p. 94</ref>}}
{{term|Saint John's Blood}}
{{defn|1=Saint John's Blood is a colloquial name for [[Polish cochineal]].}}
{{term|Saxon blue}}
{{defn|1=Saxon blue or Saxony blue is an 18th century dye made from a solution of [[indigo dye|indigo]] in concentrated [[sulphuric acid]].}}
{{term|Saxon green}}
{{defn|1=Saxon green or Saxony green is a bright green dye of the 18th century produced using [[indigo dye|indigo]] and [[Maclura tinctoria|fustic]].}}
{{term|substantive}}
{{defn|1=[[Substantive dye]]s are dyes that produce color without the use of a [[mordant]].<ref name="Cannon13" /> Examples include [[indigo dye]] and [[archil]].}}
{{term|sumac(h)}}
{{defn|1=Various species of sumac or sumach, especially [[Rhus coriaria|Elm-Leaved Sumach]] (''Rhus coriaria'') or Tanner's Sumach of southern Europe and [[Rhus typhina|Staghorn Sumac]] (''Rhus typhina'') of eastern [[North America]], are rich sources of [[tannin]]s and are used as dyes and [[mordant]]s.<ref name="Cannon118">Cannon & Cannon (2002), p. 118</ref>}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==T==
{{glossary}}
{{term|tannin}}
{{defn|1=[[Tannin]] from [[oak]] bark or [[oak apple|gall]] nuts is used as a [[mordant]].}}
{{term|tin}}
{{defn|1=[[Tin(II) chloride|Stannous chloride]], a metallic salt of [[tin]], is used as a [[mordant]] to brighten colors.<ref name="Barber235" /><ref name="Goodwin32" />}}
{{term|Turkey red}}
{{defn|1=[[Turkey red]] was a strong, very fast red dye for cotton obtained from madder root via a complicated multistep process involving "[[sumac]] and oak galls, calf's blood, sheep's dung, oil, soda, alum, and a solution of tin."<ref>Goodwin (1982), p. 65.</ref> Turkey red was developed in India and spread to Turkey. Greek workers familiar with the methods of its production were brought to France in 1747, and Dutch and English spies soon discovered the secret. A sanitized version of Turkey red was being produced in Manchester by 1784.<ref>Cannon & Cannon (2002), p. 76</ref>}}

{{term|Tyrian purple}}
{{defn|1=[[Tyrian purple]] or royal purple is a purple-red dye which is extracted from several genera of [[sea snail]]s, primarily ''[[Murex brandaris]]'' the spiny dye-murex (currently known as ''Bolinus brandaris''). Murex dye was greatly prized in antiquity because it did not fade, rather it became brighter and more intense with weathering and sunlight.<ref name="Barber228"/>}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==W==
{{glossary}}
{{term|weld}}
{{defn|1=[[Reseda (plant)|Weld]] (''Reseda luteola''), also called mignonette or dyer's rocket, was an important yellow dye of the ancient Mediterranean and Europe.<ref name="Goodwin63">Goodwin (1982), p. 63</ref>}}
{{term|woad}}
{{defn|1=[[isatis tinctoria|Woad]] (''Isatis tinctoria'') is an [[indigo dye]]-bearing indigenous plant of [[Assyria]] and the [[Levant]] which has been grown in Northern Europe over 2,000 years as a source of blue dye. Woad was carried to [[New England]] in the 17th century and used extensively in America until native stands of indigo were discovered in Florida and the Carolinas.<ref name="Goodwin70" />}}
{{glossary end}}
{{compact ToC|top=yes|name=no|short1|e=|h=|j=|v=|x=|z=|refs=yes|extlinks=no}}

==Y==
{{glossary}}
{{term|young fustic}}
{{defn|1=Young fustic is a yellow dye derived from the wood of the [[Eurasian smoketree]] (''Cotinus coggygria'').<ref name="Cannon118" />}}

{{glossary end}}
