'''Microlinguistics''' is a branch of [[linguistics]] that concerns itself with the study of [[language]] systems in the abstract, without regard to the [[Meaning (linguistics)|meaning]] or notional content of linguistic expressions. In micro-linguistics, language is reduced to the abstract mental elements of [[syntax]] and [[phonology]]. It contrasts with [[macro-linguistics]], which includes meanings, and especially with [[sociolinguistics]], which studies how language and meaning function within human social systems.<ref>{{Citation | last = Matthews | first = P.H. | author-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2002 | title = The Concise Oxford Dictionary of Linguistics | periodical = | series = | publication-place = Oxford | place = | publisher = Oxford UP | volume = | issue = | pages = | url = | issn = | pmid= | pmc= | doi = | oclc = | accessdate = }}.</ref> The term ''micro-linguistics'' was first used in print by [[George L. Trager]], in an article published in 1949 in ''Studies in Linguistics: Occasional Papers''.<ref>{{Citation | last = | first = | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | year = 1989 | date = | publication-date = | contribution = Microlinguistics | contribution-url = | editor-last = | editor-first = | editor-link = | editor2-last = | editor2-first = | editor2-link = | title = The Oxford English Dictionary | edition = 2nd | series = | place = | publication-place = | publisher = Oxford UP | volume = | pages = | id = | isbn = | doi = | oclc = | url = }}.</ref>
